(chapter
  :book                "Book of Simulation Games"
  :chapter-number      7
  :title               "The Brachistochrone"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "simulation-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + physics-simulation-emergent"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :provenance          ((:authored-by "Engineer") (:date "2026-07-16"))
  :prose
"In 1696 Johann Bernoulli posed a challenge to the mathematicians of
Europe: given two points, one above and to the left of the other, and
a ball that starts at rest, what curve connecting them lets the ball
reach the lower point in the shortest time under gravity? Straight
line? No, too slow at the start. Quarter circle? Closer, but not the
winner. The answer, discovered by Bernoulli and independently by
several others, is a cycloid — the curve traced by a point on the rim
of a rolling wheel. The problem is called the brachistochrone, from
Greek 'shortest time.'

We could work through the calculus of variations. We could set up the
Euler-Lagrange equation for the time integral and derive the cycloid.
Or we could build three slides in Motoi Scheme, drop a ball on each,
and see which wins the race. This chapter takes the second path.
Then, once you've seen the cycloid win, we'll peek at why.

---

## 7.1 Three slides

We build a straight line, a quarter arc, and the true brachistochrone.
Each is a `curve/*` object we can drop a ball on.

```scheme
(define start (vec/make 60 80))
(define stop  (vec/make 380 260))

(define straight-slide
  (curve/line start stop))

(define arc-slide
  (curve/arc start stop 'clockwise))

(define brachi-slide
  (curve/brachistochrone start stop))
```

`curve/brachistochrone` builds the correct cycloid arc between the two
points. Under the hood it solves for the cycloid parameters
`(theta_end, R)` numerically — there's no closed form for the
parameters given arbitrary endpoints — and returns a parametric
`curve/*` object.

## 7.2 Drop three balls, race them

We put a ball on each slide, let gravity roll them down, time the run.

```scheme
(define (race)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
  (let ((b1 (world/spawn 'ball (car start) (cdr start)))
        (b2 (world/spawn 'ball (car start) (cdr start)))
        (b3 (world/spawn 'ball (car start) (cdr start))))
    (entity/mass! b1 1.0)
    (entity/mass! b2 1.0)
    (entity/mass! b3 1.0)
    (curve/constrain-to! b1 straight-slide)
    (curve/constrain-to! b2 arc-slide)
    (curve/constrain-to! b3 brachi-slide)
    (list b1 b2 b3)))

(race)
```

`curve/constrain-to!` locks the ball to the curve — the ball's
position is projected onto the nearest point on the curve every
frame, and it can only move along the curve's arc-length parameter.
Gravity is applied normally; the component tangent to the curve
accelerates the ball along the curve.

Run the sim. The brachi ball arrives first, by a noticeable margin.
The arc ball second. The straight-line ball last.

## 7.3 Time the race precisely

```scheme
(define (race-timed)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.5)
  (let ((b1 (world/spawn 'ball (car start) (cdr start)))
        (b2 (world/spawn 'ball (car start) (cdr start)))
        (b3 (world/spawn 'ball (car start) (cdr start))))
    (entity/mass! b1 1.0)
    (entity/mass! b2 1.0)
    (entity/mass! b3 1.0)
    (curve/constrain-to! b1 straight-slide)
    (curve/constrain-to! b2 arc-slide)
    (curve/constrain-to! b3 brachi-slide)
    (let loop ((t 0) (arrivals '()))
      (world/step)
      (let ((arr
              (append
                (if (and (not (assoc 'straight arrivals))
                         (curve/at-end? b1 straight-slide))
                    (list (list 'straight t)) '())
                (if (and (not (assoc 'arc arrivals))
                         (curve/at-end? b2 arc-slide))
                    (list (list 'arc t)) '())
                (if (and (not (assoc 'brachi arrivals))
                         (curve/at-end? b3 brachi-slide))
                    (list (list 'brachi t)) '()))))
        (if (= 3 (+ (length arrivals) (length arr)))
            (append arrivals arr)
            (loop (+ t 1) (append arrivals arr)))))))

(race-timed)
;; => ((brachi ~72) (arc ~86) (straight ~104))
```

The brachi ball arrives in about 72 frames. The arc, 86. The straight
line, 104. The cycloid wins by about 30%.

## 7.4 Why? — analytic descent time

`curve/descent-time` gives you the analytic time to descend a curve
in a uniform gravity field.

```scheme
(list
  (list 'straight (curve/descent-time straight-slide 0.5))
  (list 'arc      (curve/descent-time arc-slide     0.5))
  (list 'brachi   (curve/descent-time brachi-slide  0.5)))
;; => ((straight ~1.72) (arc ~1.43) (brachi ~1.19))
```

Same ordering, same story. The brachistochrone is fastest because it
trades early height (a nearly-vertical drop at the start) for early
speed, then uses that speed on a gentler slope toward the endpoint.
Speed compounds: fast at the start means fast everywhere after,
because energy is conserved.

You can see this in the shape. The brachi drops steeply from the
start, then flattens. The arc has a more even slope. The straight
line has the slope you'd expect from an unimaginative geometer.

## 7.5 Design challenge: skate ramp

Given a start point 4 meters up and a finish point 6 meters over
horizontally, what shape is the fastest skate ramp?

```scheme
(define ramp
  (curve/brachistochrone (vec/make 0 4) (vec/make 6 0)))

(curve/sample ramp 30)
;; => ((0 4) (0.1 3.8) (0.3 3.5) ... (6 0))
```

Print the sample points, hand them to a builder, and you have a
fastest-time ramp. In real skate design people don't quite build
cycloids because a skateboarder doesn't roll frictionlessly — but the
brachistochrone is the theoretical bound. Any ramp shape gets you
there slower.

## 7.6 The fall path

`curve/fall-path` computes the trajectory of a ball rolling on a
gravity-affected curve WITHOUT the constraint of following the curve
exactly — the ball can also leave the curve into the air. This is
what happens on real slides when they curve away underneath a ball
that's already moving.

```scheme
(define (rollercoaster start ...)
  (let ((curve (curve/catmull-rom control-points)))
    (curve/fall-path curve start)))
```

You get a sequence of (position, velocity, on-curve?) triples for
each timestep. When the ball's centripetal-force requirement exceeds
what the curve can provide, the ball leaves the curve into the air.
This is why rollercoasters have retention bars — the coaster car
would otherwise sometimes leave the track at the top of loops.

---

## 7.7 The four routing patterns

**Composition.** The race is composed: three curves, three balls,
three `curve/constrain-to!` bindings, one shared world. Add a fourth
slide (a catenary, say — the natural hang of a chain) and you compose
one more line.

**Orchestration.** The race orchestrates 'wait for all three to
arrive' and reports the times. A rollercoaster designer's sim
orchestrates 'design curve → run fall-path → check g-forces at each
point → adjust curve → repeat.'

**In-routing.** When each ball reaches the end of its curve, the
`curve/at-end?` predicate routes to 'record arrival time.'

**Routing.** The arrival times route to a leaderboard. The paint of
each slide routes to the framebuffer as a colored curve. The
brachistochrone parameters route to an export-to-CAD file if you want
to physically build the ramp. The runtime would route the finding — 'brachi
is 30% faster than straight' — to Cortex, and next time someone asks
'which slide is fastest' she has the answer without re-simulating.

---

## 7.8 Common desktop tasks

An operator building a candy chute for a candy-shop counter asked:
'if we drop candies from the top and they need to land in the bin in
the corner, what shape should the chute be to get them there fastest
without splashing?' Brachistochrone chute, slightly flared at the
bottom to slow the arrival. The sim tells them the shape; a laser
cutter cuts the cardboard template.

## 7.9 Try this

1. Change the endpoints. Does the brachi still win?
2. Add friction (`entity/friction!`). Does the fastest curve change?
3. Race a parabola (`curve/parabola`) against the brachi. Close?
4. Two brachistochrones from different starts to the same end — do
   they arrive at the same time? (Hint: yes, if same energy — that's
   the tautochrone property, Appendix D.)
5. Design a five-second ride: what start height and horizontal
   distance give exactly 5 seconds descent on a brachi?

## 7.10 Pitfalls

**Discretization drift.** A curve sampled too coarsely and then
integrated will drift off the analytic curve. `curve/sample`
resolution matters. Use `curve/adaptive-sample` for hard cases.

**Retention.** When constraining to a curve, the ball can 'leave' if
speeds get too high. Use `curve/lock` mode for hard constraint,
`curve/gravity` mode for a rail that can be left.

**Gravity direction.** The brachistochrone formula assumes gravity is
straight down. In sideways-gravity worlds, the cycloid is rotated
along with gravity.

---

